{"nodes":[{"content":"The practice of defining UI in the form of declarative XAML markup translates extremely well from Universal 8.1 apps to Universal Windows Platform (UWP) apps.","pos":[35,193]},{"content":"Porting Windows Runtime 8.x XAML and UI to UWP'","pos":[201,248]},{"content":"Porting Windows Runtime 8.x XAML and UI to UWP","pos":[305,351]},{"content":"Updated for UWP apps on Windows 10.","pos":[356,391]},{"content":"For Windows 8.x articles, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>archive<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=619132)</ept>","pos":[392,484]},{"pos":[489,561],"content":"The previous topic was <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Troubleshooting<ept id=\"p1\">](w8x-to-uwp-troubleshooting.md)</ept>."},{"content":"The practice of defining UI in the form of declarative XAML markup translates extremely well from Universal 8.1 apps to Universal Windows Platform (UWP) apps.","pos":[563,721]},{"content":"You'll find that most of your markup is compatible, although you may need to make some adjustments to the system Resource keys or custom templates that you're using.","pos":[722,887]},{"content":"The imperative code in your view models will require little or no change.","pos":[888,961]},{"content":"Even much, or most, of the code in your presentation layer that manipulates UI elements should also be straightforward to port.","pos":[962,1089]},{"content":"Imperative code","pos":[1094,1109]},{"content":"If you just want to get to the stage where your project builds, you can comment or stub out any non-essential code.","pos":[1111,1226]},{"content":"Then iterate, one issue at a time, and refer to the following topics in this section (and the previous topic: <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Troubleshooting<ept id=\"p1\">](w8x-to-uwp-troubleshooting.md)</ept>), until any build and runtime issues are ironed-out and your port is complete.","pos":[1227,1464]},{"content":"Adaptive/responsive UI","pos":[1469,1491]},{"content":"Because your app can run on a potentially wide range of devices—each with its own screen size and resolution—you'll want to go beyond the minimal steps to port your app and you'll want to tailor your UI to look its best on those devices.","pos":[1493,1730]},{"content":"You can use the adaptive Visual State Manager feature to dynamically detect window size and to change layout in response, and an example of how to do that is shown in the section <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Adaptive UI<ept id=\"p1\">](w8x-to-uwp-case-study-bookstore2.md#adaptive-ui)</ept> in the Bookstore2 case study topic.","pos":[1731,2008]},{"content":"Back button handling","pos":[2013,2033]},{"content":"For Universal 8.1 apps, Windows Store apps and Windows Phone Store apps have different approaches to the UI you show and the events you handle for the back button.","pos":[2035,2198]},{"content":"But, for Windows 10 apps, you can use a single approach in your app.","pos":[2199,2267]},{"content":"On mobile devices, the button is provided for you as a capacitive button on the device, or as a button in the shell.","pos":[2268,2384]},{"content":"On a desktop device, you add a button to your app's chrome whenever back-navigation is possible within the app, and this appears in the title bar for windowed apps or in the task bar for Tablet mode.","pos":[2385,2584]},{"content":"The back button event is a universal concept across all device families, and buttons implemented in hardware or in software raise the same <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>BackRequested<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn893596)</ept> event.","pos":[2585,2808]},{"content":"The example below works for all device families and it is good for cases where the same processing applies to all pages, and where you do not need to confirm navigation (for example, to warn about unsaved changes).","pos":[2810,3024]},{"content":"There's also a single approach for all device families for programmatically exiting the app.","pos":[4348,4440]},{"content":"Charms","pos":[4507,4513]},{"content":"You don't need to change any of your code that integrates with charms, but you do need to add some UI to your app to take the place of the Charms bar, which is not a part of the Windows 10 shell.","pos":[4515,4710]},{"content":"A Universal 8.1 app running on Windows 10 has its own replacement UI provided by system-rendered chrome in the app's title bar.","pos":[4711,4838]},{"content":"Controls, and control styles/templates","pos":[4843,4881]},{"content":"A Universal 8.1 app running on Windows 10 will retain the 8.1 appearance and behavior with respect to controls.","pos":[4883,4994]},{"content":"But, when you port that app to a Windows 10 app, there are some differences in appearance and behavior to be aware of.","pos":[4995,5113]},{"content":"The architecture and design of controls is essentially unchanged for Windows 10 apps, so the changes are mostly around <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>design language<ept id=\"p1\">](#design-language)</ept>, simplification, and usability improvements.","pos":[5114,5313]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>   The PointerOver visual state is relevant in custom styles/templates in Windows 10 apps and in Windows Store apps, but not in Windows Phone Store apps.","pos":[5315,5476]},{"content":"For this reason (and because of the system resource keys that are supported for Windows 10 apps), we recommend that you re-use the custom styles/templates from your Windows Store apps when you're porting your app to Windows 10.","pos":[5477,5704]},{"content":"If you want to be certain that your custom styles/templates are using the latest set of visual states, and are benefitting from performance improvements made to the default styles/templates, then edit a copy of the new Windows 10 default template and re-apply your customization to that.","pos":[5705,5992]},{"content":"One example of a performance improvement is that any <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Border<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> that formerly enclosed a <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ContentPresenter<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> or a Panel has been removed and a child element now renders the border.","pos":[5993,6174]},{"content":"Here are some more specific examples of changes to controls.","pos":[6176,6236]},{"content":"Control name","pos":[6240,6252]},{"content":"Change","pos":[6255,6261]},{"content":"AppBar","pos":[6294,6300]},{"content":"If you are using the <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>AppBar<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> control (<bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>CommandBar<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept><ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh701927)</ept> is recommended instead), then it is not hidden by default in a Windows 10 app.","pos":[6307,6501]},{"content":"You can control this with the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>AppBar.ClosedDisplayMode<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn633872)</ept> property.","pos":[6502,6630]},{"pos":[6635,6721],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>AppBar<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>CommandBar<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept><ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh701927)</ept>"},{"pos":[6724,6877],"content":"In a Windows 10 app, <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>AppBar<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>CommandBar<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept><ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh701927)</ept> have a <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>See more<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept> button (the ellipsis)."},{"content":"CommandBar","pos":[6885,6895]},{"content":"In a Windows Store app, the secondary commands of a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>CommandBar<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh701927)</ept> are always visible.","pos":[6959,7105]},{"content":"In a Windows Phone Store app, and in a Windows 10 app, the don't appear until the command bar opens.","pos":[7106,7206]},{"content":"CommandBar","pos":[7214,7224]},{"content":"For a Windows Phone Store app, the value of <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>CommandBar.IsSticky<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh701944)</ept> does not affect whether or not the bar is light-dismissible.","pos":[7288,7476]},{"content":"For a Windows 10 app, if <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>IsSticky<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> is set to true, then the <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>CommandBar<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> disregards a light dismiss gesture.","pos":[7477,7590]},{"content":"CommandBar","pos":[7598,7608]},{"content":"In a Windows 10 app, <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>CommandBar<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh701927)</ept> does not handle the <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>EdgeGesture.Completed<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh701622)</ept> nor <bpt id=\"p5\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>UIElement.RightTapped<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept><ept id=\"p5\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br208984)</ept> events.","pos":[7672,7971]},{"content":"Nor does it respond to a tap nor a swipe up.","pos":[7972,8016]},{"content":"You still have the option to handle these events and set <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>IsOpen<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh701939)</ept>.","pos":[8017,8145]},{"pos":[8150,8300],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>DatePicker<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn298584)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>TimePicker<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn299280)</ept>"},{"content":"Review how your app looks with the visual changes to <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>DatePicker<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn298584)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>TimePicker<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn299280)</ept>.","pos":[8303,8510]},{"content":"For a Windows 10 app running on a mobile device, these controls no longer navigate to a selection page but instead use a light-dismissible popup.","pos":[8511,8656]},{"pos":[8661,8811],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>DatePicker<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn298584)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>TimePicker<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn299280)</ept>"},{"content":"In a Windows 10 app, you can't put <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>DatePicker<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn298584)</ept> or <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>TimePicker<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn299280)</ept> inside a fly-out.","pos":[8814,9019]},{"content":"If you want those controls to be displayed in a popup-type control, then you can use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>DatePickerFlyout<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn625013)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>TimePickerFlyout<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn608313)</ept>.","pos":[9020,9271]},{"pos":[9276,9302],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>GridView<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ListView<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>"},{"pos":[9305,9379],"content":"For <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>GridView<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept><ph id=\"ph1\">/</ph><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ListView<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>, see <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>GridView/ListView changes<ept id=\"p3\">](#gridview)</ept>."},{"content":"Hub","pos":[9387,9390]},{"content":"In a Windows Phone Store app, a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Hub<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn251843)</ept> control wraps around from the last section to the first.","pos":[9454,9610]},{"content":"In a Windows Store app, and in a Windows 10 app, hub sections do not wrap around.","pos":[9611,9692]},{"content":"Hub","pos":[9700,9703]},{"content":"In a Windows Phone Store app, a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Hub<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn251843)</ept> control's background image moves in parallax relative to the hub sections.","pos":[9767,9941]},{"content":"In a Windows Store app, and in a Windows 10 app, parallax is not used.","pos":[9942,10012]},{"content":"Hub","pos":[10020,10023]},{"content":"In a Universal 8.1 app, the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>HubSection.IsHeaderInteractive<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn251917)</ept> property causes the section header—and a chevron glyph rendered next to it—to become interactive.","pos":[10088,10308]},{"content":"In a Windows 10 app, there is an interactive \"See more\" affordance beside the header, but the header itself is not interactive.","pos":[10309,10436]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>IsHeaderInteractive<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> still determines whether interaction raises the <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Hub.SectionHeaderClick<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept><ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn251953)</ept> event.","pos":[10437,10602]},{"content":"MessageDialog","pos":[10609,10622]},{"content":"If you're using <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>MessageDialog<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, then consider instead using the more flexible <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>ContentDialog<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept><ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn633972)</ept>.","pos":[10627,10786]},{"content":"Also, see the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>XAML UI Basics<ept id=\"p1\">](http://go.microsoft.com/fwlink/p/?linkid=619992)</ept> sample.","pos":[10787,10874]},{"pos":[10879,10917],"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>ListPickerFlyout<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>PickerFlyout<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept>"},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>ListPickerFlyout<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> and <bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>PickerFlyout<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept> are deprecated for a Windows 10 app.","pos":[10921,10999]},{"content":"For a single selection fly-out, use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>MenuFlyout<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn299030)</ept>; for more complex experiences, use <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>Flyout<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn279496)</ept>.","pos":[11000,11217]},{"content":"PasswordBox","pos":[11225,11236]},{"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>PasswordBox.IsPasswordRevealButtonEnabled<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh702579)</ept> property is deprecated in a Windows 10 app, and setting it has no effect.","pos":[11300,11483]},{"content":"Use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>PasswordBox.PasswordRevealMode<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn890867)</ept> instead, which defaults to <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Peek<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> (in which an eye glyph is displayed, like in a Windows Store app).","pos":[11484,11685]},{"content":"Also, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Guidelines for password boxes<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn596103)</ept>.","pos":[11686,11786]},{"content":"Pivot","pos":[11794,11799]},{"pos":[11863,12012],"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Pivot<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn608241)</ept> control is now universal, it is no longer limited to use on mobile devices."},{"content":"SearchBox","pos":[12020,12029]},{"content":"Although <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>SearchBox<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn252803)</ept> is implemented in the Universal device family, it is not fully functional on mobile devices.","pos":[12093,12268]},{"content":"See <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>SearchBox deprecated in favor of AutoSuggestBox<ept id=\"p1\">](#searchbox)</ept>.","pos":[12269,12335]},{"content":"SemanticZoom","pos":[12342,12354]},{"pos":[12359,12424],"content":"For <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>SemanticZoom<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>, see <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>SemanticZoom changes<ept id=\"p2\">](#semantic-zoom)</ept>."},{"content":"ScrollViewer","pos":[12432,12444]},{"content":"Some default properties of <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ScrollViewer<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209527)</ept> have changed.","pos":[12509,12626]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>HorizontalScrollMode<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209549)</ept> is <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Auto<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept>, <bpt id=\"p4\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p5\">**</bpt>VerticalScrollMode<ept id=\"p5\">**</ept><ept id=\"p4\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209589)</ept> is <bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>Auto<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept>, and <bpt id=\"p7\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p8\">**</bpt>ZoomMode<ept id=\"p8\">**</ept><ept id=\"p7\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209601)</ept> is <bpt id=\"p9\">**</bpt>Disabled<ept id=\"p9\">**</ept>.","pos":[12627,12914]},{"content":"If the new default values are not appropriate for your app, then you can change them either in a style or as local values on the control itself.","pos":[12915,13059]},{"content":"TextBox","pos":[13068,13075]},{"content":"In a Windows Store app, spell-checking is off by default for a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>TextBox<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209683)</ept>.","pos":[13139,13274]},{"content":"In a Windows Phone Store app, and in a Windows 10 app, it is on by default.","pos":[13275,13350]},{"content":"TextBox","pos":[13358,13365]},{"pos":[13429,13555],"content":"The default font size for a <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>TextBox<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209683)</ept> has changed from 11 to 15."},{"content":"TextBox","pos":[13563,13570]},{"content":"The default value of <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>TextBox.TextReadingOrder<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn252859)</ept> has changed from <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Default<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> to <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>DetectFromContent<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept>.","pos":[13634,13798]},{"content":"If that's undesirable, then use <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>UseFlowDirection<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>.","pos":[13799,13852]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Default<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> is deprecated.","pos":[13853,13879]},{"content":"Various","pos":[13884,13891]},{"content":"Accent color applies to a Windows Phone Store apps, and to Windows 10 apps, but not to Windows Store apps.","pos":[13894,14000]},{"pos":[14005,14289],"content":"For more info on UWP app controls, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Controls by function<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/mt185405)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p2\">[</bpt>Controls list<ept id=\"p2\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/mt185406)</ept>, and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt>Guidelines for controls<ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn611856)</ept>."},{"content":"Design language in Windows 10","pos":[14295,14324]},{"content":"There are some small but important differences in design language between Universal 8.1 apps and Windows 10 apps.","pos":[14326,14439]},{"content":"For all the details, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Design<ept id=\"p1\">](http://dev.windows.com/design)</ept>.","pos":[14440,14505]},{"content":"Despite the design language changes, our design principles remain consistent: be attentive to detail but always strive for simplicity through focusing on content not chrome, fiercely reducing visual elements, and remaining authentic to the digital domain; use visual hierarchy especially with typography; design on a grid; and bring your experiences to life with fluid animations.","pos":[14506,14886]},{"content":"Effective pixels, viewing distance, and scale factors","pos":[14891,14944]},{"content":"Previously, view pixels were the way to abstract the size and layout of UI elements away from the actual physical size and resolution of devices.","pos":[14946,15091]},{"content":"View pixels have now evolved into effective pixels, and here's an explanation of that term, what it means, and the extra value it offers.","pos":[15092,15229]},{"content":"The term \"resolution\" refers to a measure of pixel density and not, as is commonly thought, pixel count.","pos":[15231,15335]},{"content":"\"Effective resolution\" is the way the physical pixels that compose an image or glyph resolve to the eye given differences in viewing distance and the physical pixel size of the device (pixel density being the reciprocal of physical pixel size).","pos":[15336,15580]},{"content":"Effective resolution is a good metric to build an experience around because it is user-centric.","pos":[15581,15676]},{"content":"By understanding all the factors, and controlling the size of UI elements, you can make the user's experience a good one.","pos":[15677,15798]},{"content":"Different devices are a different number of effective pixels wide, ranging from 320 epx for the smallest devices, to 1024 epx for a modest-sized monitor, and far beyond to much higher widths.","pos":[15800,15991]},{"content":"All you have to do is continue to use auto-sized elements and dynamic layout panels as you always have.","pos":[15992,16095]},{"content":"There will also be some cases where you'll set the properties of your UI elements to a fixed size in XAML markup.","pos":[16096,16209]},{"content":"A scale factor is automatically applied to your app depending on what device it runs on and the display settings made by the user.","pos":[16210,16340]},{"content":"And that scale factor serves to keep any UI element with a fixed size presenting a more-or-less constant-sized touch (and reading) target to the user across a wide variety of screen sizes.","pos":[16341,16529]},{"content":"And together with dynamic layout, your UI won't merely optically scale on different devices.","pos":[16530,16622]},{"content":"It will instead do what's necessary to fit the appropriate amount of content into the available space.","pos":[16623,16725]},{"content":"So that your app has the best experience across all displays, we recommend that you create each bitmap asset in a range of sizes, each suitable for a particular scale factor.","pos":[16727,16901]},{"content":"Providing assets at 100%-scale, 200%-scale, and 400%-scale (in that priority order) will give you excellent results in most cases at all the intermediate scale factors.","pos":[16902,17070]},{"content":"<bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Note<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>  If, for whatever reason, you cannot create assets in more than one size, then create 100%-scale assets.","pos":[17072,17185]},{"content":"In Microsoft Visual Studio, the default project template for UWP apps provides branding assets (tile images and logos) in only one size, but they are not 100%-scale.","pos":[17186,17351]},{"content":"When authoring assets for your own app, follow the guidance in this section and provide 100%, 200%, and 400% sizes, and use asset packs.","pos":[17352,17488]},{"content":"If you have intricate artwork, then you may want to provide your assets in even more sizes.","pos":[17490,17581]},{"content":"If you're starting with vector art, then it's relatively easy to generate high-quality assets at any scale factor.","pos":[17582,17696]},{"content":"We don't recommend that you try to support all of the scale factors, but the full list of scale factors for Windows 10 apps is 100%, 125%, 150%, 200%, 250%, 300%, and 400%.","pos":[17698,17870]},{"content":"If you provide them, the Store will pick the correct-sized asset(s) for each device, and only those assets will be downloaded.","pos":[17871,17997]},{"content":"The Store selects the assets to download based on the DPI of the device.","pos":[17998,18070]},{"content":"You can re-use assets from your Windows Store app at scale factors such as 140% and 220%, but your app will run at one of the new scale factors and so some bitmap scaling will be unavoidable.","pos":[18071,18262]},{"content":"Test your app on a range of devices to see whether you're happy with the results in your case.","pos":[18263,18357]},{"content":"You may be re-using XAML markup from a Windows Store app where literal dimension values are used in the markup (perhaps to size shapes or other elements, perhaps for typography).","pos":[18359,18537]},{"content":"But, in some cases, a larger scale factor is used on a device for a Windows 10 app than for a Universal 8.1 app (for example, 150% is used where 140% was before, and 200% is used where 180% was).","pos":[18538,18733]},{"content":"So, if you find that these literal values are now too big on Windows 10, then try multiplying them by 0.8.","pos":[18734,18840]},{"content":"For more info, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>Responsive design 101 for UWP apps<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn958435)</ept>.","pos":[18841,18955]},{"content":"GridView/ListView changes","pos":[18960,18985]},{"content":"Several changes have been made to the default style setters for <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>GridView<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242705)</ept> to make the control scroll vertically (instead of horizontally, as it did previously by default).","pos":[18987,19221]},{"content":"If you edited a copy of the default style in your project, then your copy won't have these changes, so you'll need to make them manually.","pos":[19222,19359]},{"content":"Here is a list of the changes.","pos":[19360,19390]},{"pos":[19396,19560],"content":"The setter for <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ScrollViewer.HorizontalScrollBarVisibility<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209547)</ept> has changed from <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Auto<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> to <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>Disabled<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept>."},{"pos":[19565,19727],"content":"The setter for <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ScrollViewer.VerticalScrollBarVisibility<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209587)</ept> has changed from <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Disabled<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> to <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>Auto<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept>."},{"pos":[19732,19890],"content":"The setter for <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ScrollViewer.HorizontalScrollMode<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209549)</ept> has changed from <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Enabled<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> to <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>Disabled<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept>."},{"pos":[19895,20051],"content":"The setter for <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ScrollViewer.VerticalScrollMode<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209589)</ept> has changed from <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Disabled<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> to <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>Enabled<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept>."},{"pos":[20056,20301],"content":"In the setter for <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ItemsPanel<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242826)</ept>, the value of <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>ItemsWrapGrid.Orientation<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn298907)</ept> has changed from <bpt id=\"p5\">**</bpt>Vertical<ept id=\"p5\">**</ept> to <bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>Horizontal<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept>."},{"content":"If that last change (the change to <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>Orientation<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept>) seems contradictory, then remember that we're talking about a wrap grid.","pos":[20303,20427]},{"content":"A horizontally-oriented wrap grid (the new value) is similar to a writing system where text flows horizontally and breaks to the next line down at the end of a page.","pos":[20428,20593]},{"content":"A page of text like that scrolls vertically.","pos":[20594,20638]},{"content":"Conversely, a vertically-oriented wrap grid (the previous value) is similar to a writing system where text flows vertically and therefore scrolls horizontally.","pos":[20639,20798]},{"pos":[20800,21026],"content":"Here are the aspects of <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>GridView<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242705)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>ListView<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242878)</ept> that have change or are not supported in Windows 10."},{"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>IsSwipeEnabled<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/hh702518)</ept> property (Windows Store apps only) is not supported for Windows 10 apps.","pos":[21032,21187]},{"content":"The API is still present, but setting it has no effect.","pos":[21188,21243]},{"content":"All previous selection gestures are supported except downward swipe (which is unsupported because data shows that it is not discoverable) and right-click (which is reserved for showing a context menu).","pos":[21244,21445]},{"content":"The <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ReorderMode<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn625099)</ept> property (Windows Phone Store apps only) is not supported for Windows 10 apps.","pos":[21450,21608]},{"content":"The API is still present, but setting it has no effect.","pos":[21609,21664]},{"content":"Instead, set <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>AllowDrop<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br208912)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>CanReorderItems<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242882)</ept> to true on your <bpt id=\"p5\">**</bpt>GridView<ept id=\"p5\">**</ept> or <bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>ListView<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept> and then the user will be able to reorder using a press-and-hold (or click-and-drag) gesture.","pos":[21665,21974]},{"content":"When developing for Windows 10, use <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ListViewItemPresenter<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn298500)</ept> instead of <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>GridViewItemPresenter<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn279298)</ept> in your item container style, both for <bpt id=\"p5\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>ListView<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept><ept id=\"p5\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242878)</ept> and for <bpt id=\"p7\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p8\">**</bpt>GridView<ept id=\"p8\">**</ept><ept id=\"p7\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242705)</ept>.","pos":[21979,22391]},{"content":"If you edit a copy of the default item container styles, then you will get the correct type.","pos":[22392,22484]},{"content":"The selection visuals have changed for a Windows 10 app.","pos":[22489,22545]},{"content":"If you set <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>SelectionMode<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242915)</ept> to <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>Multiple<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept>, then by default, a check box is rendered for each item.","pos":[22546,22707]},{"content":"The default setting for <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>ListView<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> items means that the check box is laid out inline beside the item, and as a result, the space occupied by the rest of the item will be slightly reduced and shifted.","pos":[22708,22909]},{"content":"For <bpt id=\"p1\">**</bpt>GridView<ept id=\"p1\">**</ept> items, the check box is overlaid on top of the item by default.","pos":[22910,22990]},{"content":"But, in either case, you can control the layout (Inline or Overlay) of the check boxes (with the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>CheckMode<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn913923)</ept> property) and whether they are shown at all (with the <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>SelectionCheckMarkVisualEnabled<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn298541)</ept> property) on the <bpt id=\"p5\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>ListViewItemPresenter<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept><ept id=\"p5\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/windows.ui.xaml.controls.primitives.listviewitempresenter.aspx)</ept> element inside your item container style as in the example below.","pos":[22991,23534]},{"content":"In Windows 10, the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ContainerContentChanging<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn298914)</ept> event is raised twice per item during UI virtualization: once for the reclaim, and once for the re-use.","pos":[23539,23750]},{"content":"If the value of <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>InRecycleQueue<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn279443)</ept> is <bpt id=\"p3\">**</bpt>true<ept id=\"p3\">**</ept> and you have no special reclaim work to do, then you can exit your event handler immediately with the assurance that it will be re-entered when that same item is re-used (at which time <bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>InRecycleQueue<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept> will be <bpt id=\"p5\">**</bpt>false<ept id=\"p5\">**</ept>).","pos":[23751,24081]},{"content":"a listviewitempresenter with inline check box","pos":[24402,24447]},{"content":"A ListViewItemPresenter with inline check box","pos":[24512,24557]},{"content":"a listviewitempresenter with overlaid check box","pos":[24561,24608]},{"content":"A ListViewItemPresenter with an overlaid check box","pos":[24674,24724]},{"content":"With the removal of downward swipe and right-click gestures for selection (for the reasons given above), the interaction model has changed, one consequence of which is that the <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ItemClick<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br242904)</ept> and <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>SelectionChanged<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/br209776)</ept> events are no longer mutually exclusive.","pos":[24730,25106]},{"content":"For your Windows 10 app, review your scenarios and decide whether to adopt the \"selection\" or the \"invoke\" interaction model.","pos":[25107,25232]},{"content":"For details, see <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt>How to change the interaction mode<ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/xaml/hh780625)</ept>.","pos":[25233,25350]},{"content":"There are some changes to the properties that you use to style <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>ListViewItemPresenter<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/windows.ui.xaml.controls.primitives.listviewitempresenter.aspx)</ept>.","pos":[25355,25558]},{"content":"Properties that are new are <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>CheckBoxBrush<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn913905)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>PressedBackground<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn913931)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p5\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>SelectedPressedBackground<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept><ept id=\"p5\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn913937)</ept>, and <bpt id=\"p7\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p8\">**</bpt>FocusSecondaryBorderBrush<ept id=\"p8\">**</ept><ept id=\"p7\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn898370)</ept>.","pos":[25559,25934]},{"content":"Properties that are ignored for a Windows 10 app are <bpt id=\"p1\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p2\">**</bpt>Padding<ept id=\"p2\">**</ept><ept id=\"p1\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn424775)</ept> (use <bpt id=\"p3\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p4\">**</bpt>ContentMargin<ept id=\"p4\">**</ept><ept id=\"p3\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn424773)</ept> instead), <bpt id=\"p5\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p6\">**</bpt>CheckHintBrush<ept id=\"p6\">**</ept><ept id=\"p5\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn298504)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p7\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p8\">**</bpt>CheckSelectingBrush<ept id=\"p8\">**</ept><ept id=\"p7\">](https://msdn.microsoft.com/library/windows/apps/dn298506)</ept>, <bpt id=\"p9\">[</bpt><bpt id=\"p10\">**</bp